  • Linear Regression Models
  • Prediction using linear regression

Linear regression is used to model and predict continuous outcomes with normal random errors. There are nearly an infinite number of different types of regression models and each regression model is typically defined by the distribution of the prediction errors (called "residuals") of the type of data. Logistic regression is used to model binary outcomes whereas Poisson regression is used to predict counts. In this exercise, we'll see some examples of linear regression as well as Train-test splits.

The packages we'll cover are: statsmodels, seaborn, and scikit-learn. While we don't explicitly teach statsmodels and seaborn in the Springboard workshop, those are great libraries to know.

1. Introduction to Linear Regression¶

1.1. Purpose of linear regression¶

Given a dataset containing predictor variables $X$ and outcome/response variable $Y$, linear regression can be used to:

  • Build a predictive model to predict future values of $\hat{Y}$, using new data $X^*$ where $Y$ is unknown.
  • Model the strength of the relationship between each independent variable $X_i$ and $Y$
    • Many times, only a subset of independent variables $X_i$ will have a linear relationship with $Y$
    • Need to figure out which $X_i$ contributes most information to predict $Y$
  • It is in many cases, the first pass prediction algorithm for continuous outcomes.

1.2. A Brief Mathematical Recap¶

Linear Regression is a method to model the relationship between a set of independent variables $X$ (also knowns as explanatory variables, features, predictors) and a dependent variable $Y$. This method assumes the relationship between each predictor $X$ is linearly related to the dependent variable $Y$. The most basic linear regression model contains one independent variable $X$, we'll call this the simple model.

$$ Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \epsilon$$

where $\epsilon$ is considered as an unobservable random variable that adds noise to the linear relationship. In linear regression, $\epsilon$ is assumed to be normally distributed with a mean of 0. In other words, what this means is that on average, if we know $Y$, a roughly equal number of predictions $\hat{Y}$ will be above $Y$ and others will be below $Y$. That is, on average, the error is zero. The residuals, $\epsilon$ are also assumed to be "i.i.d.": independently and identically distributed. Independence means that the residuals are not correlated -- the residual from one prediction has no effect on the residual from another prediction. Correlated errors are common in time series analysis and spatial analyses.

  • $\beta_0$ is the intercept of the linear model and represents the average of $Y$ when all independent variables $X$ are set to 0.

  • $\beta_1$ is the slope of the line associated with the regression model and represents the average effect of a one-unit increase in $X$ on $Y$.

  • Back to the simple model. The model in linear regression is the conditional mean of $Y$ given the values in $X$ is expressed a linear function.

$$ y = f(x) = E(Y | X = x)$$

Image from http://www.learner.org/courses/againstallodds/about/glossary.html. Note this image uses $\alpha$ and $\beta$ instead of $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$.

  • The goal is to estimate the coefficients (e.g. $\beta_0$ and $\beta_1$). We represent the estimates of the coefficients with a "hat" on top of the letter.

$$ \hat{\beta}_0, \hat{\beta}_1 $$

  • Once we estimate the coefficients $\hat{\beta}_0$ and $\hat{\beta}_1$, we can use these to predict new values of $Y$ given new data $X$.

$$\hat{y} = \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_1$$

  • Multiple linear regression is when you have more than one independent variable and the estimation involves matrices
    • $X_1$, $X_2$, $X_3$, $\ldots$
  • How do you estimate the coefficients?
    • There are many ways to fit a linear regression model
    • The method called least squares is the most common methods
    • We will discuss least squares

$$ Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_1 + \ldots + \beta_p X_p + \epsilon$$

1.3. Estimating $\hat\beta$: Least squares¶

Least squares is a method that can estimate the coefficients of a linear model by minimizing the squared residuals:

$$ \mathscr{L} = \sum_{i=1}^N \epsilon_i^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \hat{y}_i \right)^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N \left(y_i - \left(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i\right)\right)^2 $$

where $N$ is the number of observations and $\epsilon$ represents a residual or error, ACTUAL - PREDICTED.

Estimating the intercept $\hat{\beta_0}$ for the simple linear model¶

We want to minimize the squared residuals and solve for $\hat{\beta_0}$ so we take the partial derivative of $\mathscr{L}$ with respect to $\hat{\beta_0}$

$ \begin{align} \frac{\partial \mathscr{L}}{\partial \hat{\beta_0}} &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \hat{\beta_0}} \sum_{i=1}^N \epsilon^2 \\ &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \hat{\beta_0}} \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \hat{y}_i \right)^2 \\ &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \hat{\beta_0}} \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \left( \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) \right)^2 \\ &= -2 \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \left( \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) \right) \hspace{25mm} \mbox{(by chain rule)} \\ &= -2 \sum_{i=1}^N (y_i - \hat{\beta}_0 - \hat{\beta}_1 x_i) \\ &= -2 \left[ \left( \sum_{i=1}^N y_i \right) - N \hat{\beta_0} - \hat{\beta}_1 \left( \sum_{i=1}^N x_i \right) \right] \\ & 2 \left[ N \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i - \sum_{i=1}^N y_i \right] = 0 \hspace{20mm} \mbox{(Set equal to 0 and solve for $\hat{\beta}_0$)} \\ & N \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i - \sum_{i=1}^N y_i = 0 \\ & N \hat{\beta}_0 = \sum_{i=1}^N y_i - \hat{\beta}_1 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i \\ & \hat{\beta}_0 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N y_i - \hat{\beta}_1 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i}{N} \\ & \hat{\beta}_0 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N y_i}{N} - \hat{\beta}_1 \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i}{N} \\ & \boxed{\hat{\beta}_0 = \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_1 \bar{x}} \end{align} $

Using this new information, we can compute the estimate for $\hat{\beta}_1$ by taking the partial derivative of $\mathscr{L}$ with respect to $\hat{\beta}_1$.

$ \begin{align} \frac{\partial \mathscr{L}}{\partial \hat{\beta_1}} &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \hat{\beta_1}} \sum_{i=1}^N \epsilon^2 \\ &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \hat{\beta_1}} \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \hat{y}_i \right)^2 \\ &= \frac{\partial}{\partial \hat{\beta_1}} \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \left( \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) \right)^2 \\ &= 2 \sum_{i=1}^N \left( y_i - \left( \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) \right) \left( -x_i \right) \hspace{25mm}\mbox{(by chain rule)} \\ &= -2 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i \left( y_i - \hat{\beta}_0 - \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) \\ &= -2 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i (y_i - \hat{\beta}_0 x_i - \hat{\beta}_1 x_i^2) \\ &= -2 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i (y_i - \left( \bar{y} - \hat{\beta}_1 \bar{x} \right) x_i - \hat{\beta}_1 x_i^2) \\ &= -2 \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i y_i - \bar{y}x_i + \hat{\beta}_1\bar{x}x_i - \hat{\beta}_1 x_i^2) \\ &= -2 \left[ \sum_{i=1}^N x_i y_i - \bar{y} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i + \hat{\beta}_1\bar{x}\sum_{i=1}^N x_i - \hat{\beta}_1 \sum_{i=1}^N x_i^2 \right] \\ &= -2 \left[ \hat{\beta}_1 \left\{ \bar{x} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i - \sum_{i=1}^N x_i^2 \right\} + \left\{ \sum_{i=1}^N x_i y_i - \bar{y} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i \right\}\right] \\ & 2 \left[ \hat{\beta}_1 \left\{ \sum_{i=1}^N x_i^2 - \bar{x} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i \right\} + \left\{ \bar{y} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i - \sum_{i=1}^N x_i y_i \right\} \right] = 0 \\ & \hat{\beta}_1 = \frac{-\left( \bar{y} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i - \sum_{i=1}^N x_i y_i \right)}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i^2 - \bar{x}\sum_{i=1}^N x_i} \\ &= \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i y_i - \bar{y} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i^2 - \bar{x} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i} \\ & \boxed{\hat{\beta}_1 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i y_i - \bar{x}\bar{y}n}{\sum_{i=1}^N x_i^2 - n \bar{x}^2}} \end{align} $

The solution can be written in compact matrix notation as

$$\hat\beta = (X^T X)^{-1}X^T Y$$

We wanted to show you this in case you remember linear algebra, in order for this solution to exist we need $X^T X$ to be invertible. Of course this requires a few extra assumptions, $X$ must be full rank so that $X^T X$ is invertible, etc. Basically, $X^T X$ is full rank if all rows and columns are linearly independent. This has a loose relationship to variables and observations being independent respective. This is important for us because this means that having redundant features in our regression models will lead to poorly fitting (and unstable) models. We'll see an implementation of this in the extra linear regression example.

2.2. Scatterplots: House Price Relationships¶

Analyze relationships between different features of a house and its price through the use of scatterplots.

2.2.1. Crime Rate¶

In [6]:
sns.regplot(y="PRICE", x="CRIM", data=bos, marker='.')
plt.xlabel("Per capita crime rate by town")
plt.ylabel("House Price (1,000 USD)")
plt.title("PRICE vs. CRIM")
plt.ylim(0)

plt.show()

exp_cr = np.array(bos.CRIM[bos.PRICE == 50])
ec_min = min(exp_cr)
ec_max = max(exp_cr)
print("\n$50,000 priced homes' crime rate range: {:.2f} - {:.2f}".format(ec_min, ec_max))

$50,000 priced homes' crime rate range: 0.01 - 9.23

Crime Rate Analysis

There is a non linear relationship between the housing price and the per capita crime rate. As it can be seen from the scatter plot above, the price of a house cannot get over a price of \$20,000 if the crime rate value is above 20. The price of houses is allowed to grow to a max of $50,000 only when the crime rate drops close to zero. However, some of the most expensive houses see crime rates close to 10; this means that crime rate is not the only thing that is taken into consideration when determining the price of a house. Therefore, other features have to be taken into consideration and analyzed. Below we will explore other house features' relationship with the house's price.

2.2.2. Number of Rooms¶

In [7]:
sns.regplot(y="PRICE", x="RM", data=bos, marker='.')
plt.xlabel("Average number of rooms per dwelling")
plt.ylabel("House Price (1,000 USD)")
plt.title("PRICE vs. RM")
plt.ylim(0)
plt.show()

exp_room = np.array(bos.RM[bos.PRICE == 50])

er_max = max(exp_room)
print("\n$50,000 priced homes' average no. of rooms range: {} - {}".format(er_min, er_max))

$50,000 priced homes' average no. of rooms range: 4.97 - 8.725

No. of Rooms Analysis

The relationship between the number of rooms in a house and its price is directly proportional, or positively linear; this relationship is more linear than the one between crime rate and house price. However, the housing price vs. average number of rooms scatterplot still shows a discrepancy when you get to the most expensive houses, becasue houses are able to achieve a maximum price of \$50,000 with an average of about 5 rooms which is on the lower end of the spectrum. This further confirms that a single house feature does not give the full picture regarding what constitutes the price of a house, and a combination of multiple house features will have to be used by the fitted model to deduce a nuanced, accurate house price.

2.2.3. Pupil-Teacher Ratio¶

In [8]:
sns.regplot(y="PRICE", x="PTRATIO", data=bos, marker='.')
plt.xlabel("Pupil-teacher ratio by town")
plt.ylabel("House Price (1,000 USD)")
plt.title("PRICE vs. PTRATIO")
plt.ylim(0)
plt.show()

Pupil-Teacher Ratio Analysis

The pupil-teacher ratio tells us how many students a single teacher is responsible for, and therefore, the higher the ratio the more students a single teacher is responsible for; a lower ratio is conducive for a better education, because each student will get more time with direct mentorship from the teacher. However, more teachers means a higher cost of schooling and is paid for by the community; therefore, it makes sense that a lower PT ratio will lead to higher house prices. This conclusion can be observed in the scatterplot above; the relationship between the PT ratio and the house price is more variant than the relationships previously observed but can still be seen. As the PT ratio value decreases the prices of the houses increase; in other words, there is an inversely proportional relationship between the PT ratio and house price.

2.2.4. Lower Status¶

In [9]:

Lower Status Analysis

The relationship between the percentage of the population that is considered lower status and the house price is one of the clearest seen so far. As it can be seen above, as the percentage of the population considered to be of lower status increases, the price of the house decreases. The relationship is not linearly defined, but can be easily represented by a reciprocal function; the house prices drop rapidly as LSTAT percentages increase at the lower end of the LSTAT percentage range but begin leveling out as LSTAT percentages increase to the higher end of the LSTAT percentage range.

Accessibility to Radial Highways Analysis

There is a slight negative correlation between the accessiblity of radial highways and the prices of houses; in effect, the more accessible a highway is to a certain house area, the higher the prices of the houses. This makes sense, because being able to easiliy access a radial highway means it will be easier to get around Boston. Therefore, if you want to get around Boston with less difficulty, you might end up paying a little more to get a house with easy access to the city's radial highways.

Crime Rate: Log vs. Non-Log Analysis

The left histogram above represents the distribution of the crime rates per capita without the log taken, and it can be noted that the majority of the crime rates are close to zero. In order to illustrate the crime rate distribution better, the log can be taken, because the log function transforms values below 1 to negative values and emphasizes small differences between values close to zero. The right histogram shows the crime rate distribution after the log function is applied. A value of zero in this histogram represents a crime rate of 1, and it can be noted that the crime rate values close to zero, which were grouped together by the original histogram, have a distribution of their own. There are two peaks in the logged histogram with log values of -2.5 and 2 which equate to crime rate values of 0.003 and 100, respectively. Overall, from the left histogram we can conclude that the majority of crime rate values are near zero, but from the right histogram, we can observe those near-zero crime rate values are centered around a crime rate value of 0.003.

3. Linear Regression with Boston Housing Data Example¶

Here,

$Y$ = boston housing prices (called "target" data in python, and referred to as the dependent variable or response variable)

and

$X$ = all the other features (or independent variables, predictors or explanatory variables)

which we will use to fit a linear regression model and predict Boston housing prices. We will use the least-squares method to estimate the coefficients.

We'll use two ways of fitting a linear regression. We recommend the first but the second is also powerful in its features.

3.1. Fitting Linear Regression using statsmodels¶

Statsmodels is a great Python library for a lot of basic and inferential statistics. It also provides basic regression functions using an R-like syntax, so it's commonly used by statisticians. While we don't cover statsmodels officially in the Data Science Intensive workshop, it's a good library to have in your toolbox. Here's a quick example of what you could do with it. The version of least-squares we will use in statsmodels is called ordinary least-squares (OLS). There are many other versions of least-squares such as partial least squares (PLS) and weighted least squares (WLS).

In [14]:
# Import regression modules
import statsmodels.api as sm
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols

RM Linear Regression Model¶

# statsmodels works nicely with pandas dataframes

3.1.1. Interpreting coefficients¶

There is a ton of information in this output. But we'll concentrate on the coefficient table (middle table). We can interpret the RM coefficient (9.1021) by first noticing that the p-value (under P>|t|) is so small, basically zero. This means that the number of rooms, RM, is a statisticall significant predictor of PRICE. The regression coefficient for RM of 9.1021 means that on average, each additional room is associated with an increase of $\$9,100$ in house price net of the other variables. The confidence interval gives us a range of plausible values for this average change, about ($\$8,279, \$9,925$), definitely not chump change.

In general, the $\hat{\beta_i}, i > 0$ can be interpreted as the following: "A one unit increase in $x_i$ is associated with, on average, a $\hat{\beta_i}$ increase/decrease in $y$ net of all other variables."

On the other hand, the interpretation for the intercept, $\hat{\beta}_0$ is the average of $y$ given that all of the independent variables $x_i$ are 0.

3.1.2. statsmodels formulas¶

This formula notation will seem familiar to R users, but will take some getting used to for people coming from other languages or are new to statistics.

The formula gives instruction for a general structure for a regression call. For statsmodels (ols or logit) calls you need to have a Pandas dataframe with column names that you will add to your formula. In the below example you need a pandas data frame that includes the columns named (Outcome, X1,X2, ...), but you don't need to build a new dataframe for every regression. Use the same dataframe with all these things in it. The structure is very simple:

Outcome ~ X1

But of course we want to to be able to handle more complex models, for example multiple regression is doone like this:

Outcome ~ X1 + X2 + X3

In general, a formula for an OLS multiple linear regression is

Y ~ X1 + X2 + ... + Xp

This is the very basic structure but it should be enough to get you through the homework. Things can get much more complex. You can force statsmodels to treat variables as categorical with the C() function, call numpy functions to transform data such as np.log for extremely-skewed data, or fit a model without an intercept by including - 1 in the formula. For a quick run-down of further uses see the statsmodels help page.

Let's see how our model actually fit our data. We can see below that there is a ceiling effect, we should probably look into that. Also, for large values of $Y$ we get underpredictions, most predictions are below the 45-degree gridlines.

Intercept Term Analysis

Scikit-learn's linear regression object has a parameter fit_intercept that sets whether or not to use a y-intercept in predictions; if this parameter is set to False, the y-intercept will be essentially zero. This is useful for situations where you already have a model making predictions, but you would like to add in another variable through the use of another model without changing the original model; there, you would want to set fit_intercept to False, because you already have predictions centered around the common house values and only want to factor in another variable.

Independently and Identically Distributed (i.i.d.) Analysis

In order for a linear regression model to do a fairly good job at predicting target variables, it is logical for the residuals to be normally distributed, because normally distributed residuals means that the prediction line would symmetrically dissect the observed targets. However, having normally distributed residuals is not the only condition needed for the assumption of residuals being independently and identically distributed, or i.i.d. for short, to be met, because residuals being normally distributed only fulfills the identically distributed aspect of the i.i.d. assumption. The independent aspect of the i.i.d. is met when you have residuals that are not correlated with one another; for example, if the target variables were correlated to one another with respect to time, as is seen in time series data, the residuals acquired by the linear model would also be correlated with one another with respect to time, and this would violate the independent aspect of the i.i.d. assumption. Luckily, the features used to predict the Boston house prices are independent of one another, and the house prices are, therefore, also independent of one another. Even though the target variable being predicted has to be independently distributed for the residuals to meet the independent aspect of the i.i.d. assumption, the target variable does not have to be normally distributed for the identically distributed aspect of the residuals' i.i.d. assumption to be met. The reason for this is that the linear model's only goal is to minimize the least squares which is calculated one target variable at a time due to the met independent condition of i.i.d., and therefore, the overall distribution of the target variable is not taken into consideration by the linear regression model.

Statsmodels vs. Scikit-learn

After using the linear regressor from statsmodels and scikit-learn, it can be noted that statsmodels returns a lot more information regarding the fitted linear model; for example, it returns the skew of the residual distribution which further confirms normality. However, because statsmodels was created with R in mind, in order to implement it in Python, the user will have to learn how to create R formulas; scikit-learn's linear regression, on the other hand, has an intuitive Python implementation in Python, since it does not require any extra parameter learning and behaves just like any other function in Python. Therefore, it depends on how much information you want to know about the model; if you want as much information about the model and the data used to arrive at the mode, statsmodels is the way to go. However, if all you need is a model capable of predictive features and its R2 score to measure its performance, scikit-learn's linear regression is what you should use.

3.2.5. Evaluating the Model: Sum-of-Squares¶

The partitioning of the sum-of-squares shows the variance in the predictions explained by the model and the variance that is attributed to error.

$$TSS = ESS + RSS = \sum_{i=1}^N \left(y_i - \bar{y} \right)^2$$

Residual Sum-of-Squares (aka $RSS$)¶

The residual sum-of-squares is one of the basic ways of quantifying how much error exists in the fitted model. We will revisit this in a bit.

$$ RSS = \sum_{i=1}^N r_i^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N \left(y_i - \left(\beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i\right)\right)^2$$

In [23]:
RSS = np.round(np.sum((bos.PRICE - lm.predict(X)) ** 2), 2)
print('RSS =', RSS)

RSS = 11078.78

Explained Sum-of-Squares (aka $ESS$)¶

The explained sum-of-squares measures the variance explained by the regression model.

$$ESS = \sum_{i=1}^N \left( \hat{y}_i - \bar{y} \right)^2 = \sum_{i=1}^N \left( \left( \hat{\beta}_0 + \hat{\beta}_1 x_i \right) - \bar{y} \right)^2$$

In [24]:
ESS = np.round(np.sum((lm.predict(X) - np.mean(bos.PRICE)) ** 2), 2)
print('ESS =', ESS)

ESS = 31637.51

3.2.6. Evaluating the Model: The Coefficient of Determination ($R^2$)¶

The coefficient of determination, $R^2$, tells us the percentage of the variance in the response variable $Y$ that can be explained by the linear regression model.

$$ R^2 = 1 - \frac{RSS}{TSS} = \frac{ESS}{TSS}$$

The $R^2$ value is one of the most common metrics that people use in describing the quality of a model, but it is important to note that $R^2$ increases artificially as a side-effect of increasing the number of independent variables. While $R^2$ is reported in almost all statistical packages, another metric called the adjusted $R^2$ is also provided as it takes into account the number of variables in the model, and can sometimes even be used for non-linear regression models!

$$R_{adj}^2 = 1 - \left( 1 - R^2 \right) \frac{N - 1}{N - K - 1} = R^2 - \left( 1 - R^2 \right) \frac{K}{N - K - 1} = 1 - \frac{\frac{RSS}{DF_R}}{\frac{TSS}{DF_T}}$$

where $N$ is the number of observations, $K$ is the number of variables, $DF_R = N - K - 1$ is the degrees of freedom associated with the residual error and $DF_T = N - 1$ is the degrees of the freedom of the total error.

3.2.7. Evaluating the Model: Mean Squared Error and the $F$-Statistic¶

The mean squared errors are just the averages of the sum-of-squares errors over their respective degrees of freedom.

$$MSE = \frac{RSS}{N-K-1}$$

$$MSR = \frac{ESS}{K}$$

Remember: Notation may vary across resources particularly the use of $R$ and $E$ in $RSS/ESS$ and $MSR/MSE$. In some resources, E = explained and R = residual. In other resources, E = error and R = regression (explained). This is a very important distinction that requires looking at the formula to determine which naming scheme is being used.

Given the MSR and MSE, we can now determine whether or not the entire model we just fit is even statistically significant. We use an $F$-test for this. The null hypothesis is that all of the $\beta$ coefficients are zero, that is, none of them have any effect on $Y$. The alternative is that at least one $\beta$ coefficient is nonzero, but it doesn't tell us which one in a multiple regression:

$$H_0: \beta_i = 0, \mbox{for all $i$} \\ H_A: \beta_i > 0, \mbox{for some $i$}$$

$$F = \frac{MSR}{MSE} = \left( \frac{R^2}{1 - R^2} \right) \left( \frac{N - K - 1}{K} \right)$$

Once we compute the $F$-statistic, we can use the $F$-distribution with $N-K$ and $K-1$ degrees of degrees of freedom to get a p-value.

Warning! The $F$-statistic mentioned in this section is NOT the same as the F1-measure or F1-value.

Coefficients & Intercept Analysis

The coefficient derived for PTRATIO is -2.1573 which means that for every additional student a teacher is responsible of, the price of the house decreases on average by \$2,157.30. The intercept acquired has a value corresponding to a house price of \\$62, 344.60 and lets us know what starting price of a house is. The reason for the intercept being such a high value is that PTRATIO is always positive and can only make the house price decrease due to its assigned negative coefficient; if the intercept was zero, for example, the linear model would constantly predict negative house prices which would lead to very poor performance.

R-Squared & F-statistic Analysis

We can measure a model's performance using the R-squared metric. The R-squared metric tells us how much of the variance was captured by the model; a value of 1 indicates the maximum R-square score a model can get which means the model predicted all of the observed data points perfectly, and a value of 0 means that the model did just as well as if the prediction was made at random. Further, a negative R-squared value means that the model is really doing bad to the point where it would have achieved a better performance if it had arrived at predictions randomly; for example, if a target value increases as a predictor variable increases, but the model predicts the target value to decrease as the predictor variable increases, that model will probably have a negative R-squared score. The linear model using PTRATIO only to predict Boston house prices achieved an R-squared score of 0.258 which means it performed better than random predictions but missed more than 70% of the dataset's variation, i.e. poor performance. The F-statistic now tells us how credible the fit of the linear regression model is; the F-statistic takes into consideration the number of observations, number of features and the R-squared score. The probability of the model being statistically significant increases as the observations increase, features decrease and R-squared score gets closer to 1. The F-statistic is then used to acquire the probability that the observations and features used acquired the R-squared score by luck; if the probability is higher than 0.05, we can accept this hypothesis, but if its lower, we can reject the hypothesis and assume that the linear model has predictor capabilities able to predict the target variable better than random. In this case, the linear model got an F-statistic of 175.1 which corresponded to a probability of 1.61e-34; therefore, we can reject the belief that the linear model's coefficient assigned to PTRATIO has no effect on the price of a house and assume there is a predictive relationship there. In a simple linear regression model, the t-statistic for the only predictor can be obtained by taking the square root of the F-statistic, because the F-statistic is calculated using the slope of the only predictor which in this case is PTRATIO.

4. Comparing Models¶

During modeling, there will be times when we want to compare models to see which one is more predictive or fits the data better. There are many ways to compare models, but we will focus on two.

4.1. The $F$-Statistic Revisited¶

The $F$-statistic can also be used to compare two nested models, that is, two models trained on the same dataset where one of the models contains a subset of the variables of the other model. The full model contains $K$ variables and the reduced model contains a subset of these $K$ variables. This allows us to add additional variables to a base model and then test if adding the variables helped the model fit.

$$F = \frac{\left( \frac{RSS_{reduced} - RSS_{full}}{DF_{reduced} - DF_{full}} \right)}{\left( \frac{RSS_{full}}{DF_{full}} \right)}$$

where $DF_x = N - K_x - 1$ where $K_x$ is the number of variables in model $x$.

4.2. Akaike Information Criterion (AIC)¶

Another statistic for comparing two models is AIC, which is based on the likelihood function and takes into account the number of variables in the model.

$$AIC = 2 K - 2 \log_e{L}$$

where $L$ is the likelihood of the model. AIC is meaningless in the absolute sense, and is only meaningful when compared to AIC values from other models. Lower values of AIC indicate better fitting models.

statsmodels provides the AIC in its output.

F_stat = ((RSS_red - RSS_full) / (DF_red - DF_full)) / (RSS_full / DF_full)
print('F-Statistic: {:.2f}'.format(F_stat))
Prob = 1 - stats.f.cdf(F_stat, DF_red, DF_full)
print('Prob (F-statistic): {:.2e}'.format(Prob))
print('--------------------------------------------')
print('    Five Variable (Full) Model AIC: {:.2f}'.format(m_five.aic))
print('Three Variable (Reduced) Model AIC: {:.2f}'.format(m_CRP.aic))

Comparing Models

After taking into account the LSTAT and DIS features of a house, on top of the CRIM, PTRATIO and RM features already used, the linear regression model was able to acquire an R-squared score of 0.696; this is more than a 0.1 increase in R-squared score of 0.594 obtained from the reduced, linear model only using the three features. However, because the R-squared score artifially increases as the features used increases, in order to test whether or not this increase in performance is really due to the newly included features and not due to chance or the increase in features, a F-test has to be done using both models' residual sum of squares and their corresponding degrees of freedom; the full equation can be seen above. After performing the necessary calculations, a probability based on the F-statistic of 1.11e-16 was arrived upon. This means that we can reject the null hypothesis that the increase in the R-squared score seen in the full model is due to chance, and assume the increase is statistically significant until proven otherwise. Further, the AIC values of two models can also be used compare the performance of the two models by taking into consideration, among other things, the number of features used, and the model with the lowest AIC is concluded to be the better performing model of the two. The reduced model achieved an AIC score of 3,231.95, while the full model achieved an AIC score of 2,973.08; therefore, the AIC scores of both models further confirm the better performance achieved by the linear regression model using the five house features.

5. Evaluating the Model via Model Assumptions and Other Issues¶

5.1. Model Assumptions¶

Linear regression makes several assumptions. It is always best to check that these assumptions are valid after fitting a linear regression model.

Linearity

The dependent variable $Y$ is a linear combination of the regression coefficients and the independent variables $X$. This can be verified with a scatterplot of each $X$ vs. $Y$ and plotting correlations among $X$. Nonlinearity can sometimes be resolved by transforming one or more independent variables, the dependent variable, or both. In other cases, a generalized linear model or a nonlinear model may be warranted.

Constant standard deviation

The SD of the dependent variable $Y$ should be constant for different values of X. We can check this by plotting each $X$ against $Y$ and verifying that there is no "funnel" shape showing data points fanning out as $X$ increases or decreases. Some techniques for dealing with non-constant variance include weighted least squares (WLS), robust standard errors, or variance stabilizing transformations.

Normal distribution for errors

The $\epsilon$ term we discussed at the beginning are assumed to be normally distributed. This can be verified with a fitted values vs. residuals plot and verifying that there is no pattern, and with a quantile plot. $$ \epsilon_i \sim N(0, \sigma^2)$$ Sometimes the distributions of responses $Y$ may not be normally distributed at any given value of $X$. e.g. skewed positively or negatively.

Independent errors

The observations are assumed to be obtained independently; e.g. Observations across time may be correlated

5.2. Other Issues¶

There are some other issues that are important investigate with linear regression models.

Correlated Predictors

Care should be taken to make sure that the independent variables in a regression model are not too highly correlated. Correlated predictors typically do not majorly affect prediction, but do inflate standard errors of coefficients making interpretation unreliable. Common solutions are dropping the least important variables involved in the correlations, using regularlization, or, when many predictors are highly correlated, considering a dimension reduction technique such as principal component analysis (PCA).

Influential Points

Data points that have undue influence on the regression model. These points can be high leverage points or outliers. Such points are typically removed and the regression model rerun.

Fitted Values vs. Residuals

The fitted values vs. residuals plot allows us to see where the average residual value lies for every price value predicted by the linear regression model, and in this case, it can be seen how the average residual value around the extreme ends of the predicted prices diverge strongly from a residual value of zero. The residuals at the extremes are positive which means that the linear model is constantly underpredicting the house prices at both ends. This is due to the linear model's attempt to linearly fit data that is not linearly separable and make residuals normally distributed; this causes the predicted values to follow a rigid linear regression line that undervalues houses at both ends of the spectrum. Further, the rigidity of the linear model causes it to place a higher importance on predicted values around \$20,000 where the residuals are closer to zero, even if it means it will receive a high penalty for the higher residual values seen at the extreme house prices, because the impact of those higher residuals does not outweigh the impact caused by the cluster of residuals corresponding to house prices around \\$20,000.

Standardized Residuals Quantile Plot

A quantile plot shows what perfectly normally distributed residuals would look like (red line) and shows us the actual distribution followed by the residuals (blue scatter plot). The same pattern seen in the fitted values plot can be seen in the quantile plot, where the linear model underpredicts the house values at the low and high price values; this is shown by the blue scatter points above the red line. The quantile plot showcases the linear model's goal to make the residuals normally distributed, since the residuals distribution does have a mean of zero.

Advantages and Disadvantages of Both Plots

The advantage of a fitted values vs. residuals plot is that you are able to see the range of the residuals and how bad the linear model's mistakes are; for example, it can be seen that there are a few residual outliers that indicate a prediction mistake of +\$20,000 dollars. These outliers will be further examined in the next section where we will decide if some observations should be removed, in order to improve the linear model's performance. Also, the fitted values vs. residuals allows us to see where the biggest mistakes are being made, because you can take the fitted value and add the residual to see what the true house price was. For example, one of the biggest resdiuals has a value of 40 which means that the linear model undervalued the house by \\$40,000, and after adding this residual to the fitted value, we can see that the actual house price was \$50,000 but was predicted to be \\$10,000; this is just one of the examples where the linear model compromises on values on the extreme ends of the price spectrum, even if it leads to large residuals. A disadvantage of the fitted values vs. resdiuals is that it does not really emphasize the distribution of the residuals and that is where the quantile plot comes in. The quantile plot emphasizes where the residuals deviate from normality by plotting them against a line representing a perfect normal distribution; for example, the quantile plot lets us see how the linear model's residuals deviate strongly from the normal distribution, especially as the standardized residuals reach a value of 4, but as it can be seen from the quantile plot, there is very few residuals deviating from normality which is due to the very few observations of houses, specifically the \$50,000 houses, that really deviated from the linear model's fitted line. We are now going to plot a leverage and cook's distance plot to take a closer look at the observations causing the residual outliers and see how it affects the model's performance if they are removed.

Leverage Plot

The leverage plot allows us to see observations with leverage outliers; leverage lets us know what observations contain feature values that are way higher or lower than the average observation. Therefore, by looking at the leverage plot, we can see how there are five observations that have a leverage higher than 0.05, and after further inspection it can be seen that the values recorded for their CRIM feature is what is causing the high leverage. From the feature statistics table, it can be seen that the average observation has a CRIM value of 3.61; half of the observations have a CRIM value below 0.26; and 75% of all observations have a CRIM value less than 3.68. Then, looking at the high leverage observations table, we can see how the observations corresponding to a leverage value greater than 0.05 have CRIM values way higher than the rest; this causes the linear model to constantly underpredict the house price which affects the fit of the model when it tries to compensate for those underpredictions. We will remove those observations with high leverage in the next step and see how it affects the linear model's performance.

Cook's Distance

The cook's distance allows us to see some of the observations' residuals that are disproportionately bigger than the rest, and therefore, even if in small quantity, these observations have a large influence in the final fit of the linear model. In order to stop any one observation from influencing the linear model too much, we will remove the observations with a cook's distance greater than 0.05; those observations can be seen in the residual outliers table. After observing this table, it can be noted that the RM feature appears to be causing the great residuals in predictions, because their room values and their corresponding price values do not follow the trend originally described where house prices should go up as rooms increase. Therefore, the house price for observation 364 was overvalued due to its unusually high room value but average true price; on the other hand, the rest of the observations with a high cook's distance were undervalued model due to the same reason which is that their RM value is lower than average but higher than average price. Observation 367 is also affected by its unusually high CRIM value, which drops the predicted price further than the actual price. These outliers will be removed in the next section, and we will see how the model's performance is affected by their removal.

Removed Outliers & High Leverage Observations

After removing the five high leverage and four outlier observations from the Boston dataset, a linear regression model using the same house features was able to go from an adjusted R-squared score of 0.592 to an adjusted R-squared score of 0.664. Therefore, it can be concluded that the removal of the high leverage and outlier observations, even if they only accounted for about 0.018% of the data, definitely helped improve the fit of the linear regression model. This makes sense as the model did not have to take into account the observations that made fitting the linear model to the Boston dataset much trickier, since those observations went against the linear trends connecting the predictor variables and the target variable or had predictor values way higher than the average observations.
